"Yap"  wrote ...

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What video is public domain?
">

Content which was produced by the US government
and released to the public. We taxpayers paid for it
and it is "ours".  For example stills/video from NASA.

Other content which is marked as "public domain"

Copyright-protected content which is so old that the
term has expired.  Dunno that any *video* is that old
yet?

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Or perhaps I should ask, what content is usable without royalty?

&gt; Are any of these?
&gt; 1. George W Bush speeches and meet-the-press briefings
&gt; 2. Other public officials in the US
&gt; 3. Non-US public officials' speeches
">

Sure, if you shot the video yourself, or you paid
someone to do it for you.  If someone else shot it,
then it belongs to them.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; 4. The George W Bush giving the middle finger video (&quot;victory finger&quot;)
">

Do you think that somehow the content changes the rules?

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; 5. Video content recorded from CSPAN
">

is owned by CSPAN. If you are talking about coverage
of Congressional sessions/hearings, etc. it is easy enough
to inquire.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; 6. Movies whose copyright was obtained over 40 years ago?
">

Easy enough to look up the current law to see when the
copyright expires. 40 years sounds like a bogus and
arbitrary number to me.  Note that copyright terms have
been changing lately due to recent legislation such as
that purchased by the Disney organization, etc. They are
longer than you think, way longer than 40 years.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; 7. Can I use withou royalty clips of mainstream
&gt; movies less than 10 seconds?
">

For what?  There are specific defenses to copyright
infringement for things like legitimate educational use,
parody, reviews, etc.  I'd suspect that the answer for
you is "no" without knowing more about what your
intended use is.
