It can, under very rare circumstances.  Courts have acknowledged in dicta
(meaning a non-binding opinion) something which has come to be known as the
Zapruder Doctrine.  It applies to film and/or video that is of events of
such historic importance that medium of the expression becomes the
expression itself.  The classic example given is the Zapruder film of the
Kennedy assassination.  It is noteworthy not only for what it captures, but
for the fact of its having been made, being the only film that records the
actual moment of assassination, etc.

I am unaware of any case in which the Zapruder doctrine has been
successfully raised as a defense to infringement.  I have, however, recently
advised a client who wanted to use a short piece of someone else's footage
in a documentary that I believed the Zapruder doctrine should apply (sorry,
can't discuss details).

&lt;remaining accurate analysis snipped?
